1. Summary

Lake ecosystems are negatively affected by anthropogenic activities that change the chemical composition of the water, such as pollution or run-off causing eutrophication. ChlorophyllÂ a (C55H72O5N4Mg) is the most important pigment of phytoplankton. The amount of phytoplankton, and thus the chlorophyllÂ a concentration, in a lake increases with increasing eutrophication.

ChlorophyllÂ a is one of the indicators that is measured and reported in connection with the Water Framework Directive (hereafter WFD). In Norway, the WFD is implemented by means of Vannforskriften, and relevant indicators (âparametersâ, in WFD terminology) are described in national guidelines (DGVF 2025). The data collected are archived and made available in the VannmiljÃ¸ database.

These WFD data can be used in other contexts, including ecological condition assessments. The procedure implemented here follows a dataflow that has been described and documented earlier (Sandvik 2019, Sandvik 2025) and that consists of the following steps:

  • Selecting measurements from the relevant time period.
  • Removing measurements that do not fulfil the requirements for the specific indicator.
  • Identifying the water body for each measurement.
  • Scaling and transforming measurements to âmodified Ecological Quality Ratiosâ according to the normative definitions for âecological statusâ categories provided by the WFD.
  • Fitting a linear model to the measurements, with explanatory variables being typology factors of the water bodies, reporting periods, and surveillance activities.
  • Averaging measurements taken in the same water body.
  • Extrapolating mEQR values to water bodies that lack data, based on the model fitted.
  • Using simulations to estimate confidence and prediction intervals.
  • Aggregating estimates geographically using area-weighted averages.
  • Truncating the values obtained to the interval from 0 to 1.

2. About the underlying data

WFD data in Norway are collected in a common database called VannmiljÃ¸, which is maintained by the Norwegian Environment Agency. This database contains information on all measurements taken in connection with the WFD (âregistrationsâ) as well as all locations at which measurements are taken (âwater localitiesâ). Each water locality is assigned to a water body. Information on water bodies can be retrieved from two other databases: the typology of water bodies is available from Vann-nett, whereas a geospatial dataset can be downloaded from the Norwegian Environment Agency.

All data used are publicly available, but not all of them are machine-readable (for details, see Datasets below).

2.1 Spatial and temporal resolution and extent

The spatial resolution of WFD indicators is on the level of water bodies. The WFD defines a water body (specifically a âbody of surface waterâ) as âa discrete and significant element of surface water such as a lake, a reservoir, a stream, river or canal, [or] part of a stream, river or canalâ (WFD, Article 2, paragraph 10; cf.Â Vannforskriften Â§Â 3, letter a; for implementation, see DGVF 2018, ch.Â 2).

There is no specific temporal resolution, as measurements of WFD indicators are reported sporadically. Some water bodies are sampled regularly (e.g., every fifth year). For most water bodies, however, no such fixed surveillance schemes exist. Still, the total amount of measurements for many WFD indicators is sufficient to estimate annual values that are spatially aggregated to the national and regional level.

A specific requirement for chlorophyllÂ a is that the indicator value for a given water body in a given year is to be based on annual averages of measurements that are taken at least monthly throughout the growing season (JuneâSeptember in Northern Norway and MayâOctober in the rest of Norway; DGVF 2025).

2.2 Original units

The concentration of chlorophyllÂ a (C55H72O5N4Mg) in water is measured in Âµg/L. However, in the connection with the WFD, values are normally reported as ânormalised ecological quality ratiosâ (nEQR) between 0 and 1, which correspond to indicator values sensu SEEA EA.

3. Indicator properties

3.1 Ecosystem Condition Typology Class (ECT)

The ECT of chlorophyllÂ a is B2 (structural state) because the indicator is an aggregate property (mass) of one of the main biotic components (phytoplankton) of lake ecosystems.

3.2 Ecosystem condition characteristic

Intact lake ecosystems are characterised by having relatively low chlorophyllÂ a concentrations, and increasing levels represent the organic pollution of lakes.

3.3 Other standards

In the Norwegian classification of ecological characteristics (Ã¸kologiske egenskaper) according to NybÃ¸ & Evju (2017, p.Â 35), the indicator represents primary production (primÃ¦rproduksjon).

In the WFDâs distinction between quality elements, the indicator represents phytoplankton (WFD, AnnexÂ V).

Eurostat has listed chlorophyllÂ a concentration as a voluntary condition variable for reporting in connection with the EU Regulation 2024/3024 (EU 2024, AnnexÂ IX; cf.Â CzÃºz el at. 2025).

The WFD enforces the environmental objectives that water bodies shall not have an indicator value below X60, and that water bodies already obtaining an indicator value above X80 shall not drop below this threshold (WFD, Article 4; cf.Â Vannforskriften Â§Â 4).

3.4 Collinearities with other indicators

ChlorophyllÂ a is correlated to other measures of lake eutrophication, specifically phytoplankton biomass, total phosphorus and PTI.

3.5 Impact factors

ChlorophyllÂ a concentration is affected by eutrophication and organic pollution, which can be the result from local or up-stream run-off (e.g.Â from fertilisers), direct pollution, or long distance pollution.

4. Reference condition and levels

4.1 Reference condition

The WFD defines the reference condition of a water body as âthe condition of a quality element where there is little or no human impact on the water body. The reference condition is therefore also referred to as the natural conditionâ (DGVF 2025).

Reference conditions may be specific to certain water-body types. Water bodies judged to be in the reference condition are referred to as reference water bodies.

4.2 Reference levels

According to the WFD, reference levels are defined for X0, X20, X40, X60, X80, and X100. These are used to classify the âecological statusâ of water bodies as âbadâ (X0 â¤ X â¤ X20), âpoorâ (X20 < X â¤ X40), âmoderateâ (X40 < X â¤ X60), âgoodâ (X60 < X â¤ X80), and âhighâ (X80 < X â¤ X100). The WFD (AnnexÂ V, sectionÂ 1.2) provides the following normative definition of âhigh statusâ: âThe values of the biological quality elements for the surface water body reflect those normally associated with that type under undisturbed conditions, and show no, or only very minor, evidence of distortion.â An approach used for many WFD indicators, including this one, is to define X100 as the median of the variable values measured in reference water bodies.

Reference levels for chlorophyllÂ a are provided in Tables 4.2 and 4.4 of DGVF (2025). These tables do not define a value for X0, since the worst possible value is practically unbounded upwards (although, strictly speaking, there is a physical ceiling at 1.08Â Â·Â 109Â Âµg/L, which is the density of pure chlorophyllÂ a). However, the calculation of nEQR (or indicator) values is based on the inverse of the variable values (see DGVF 2025, Table 3.11), meaning that an infinite X0 is unproblematic. For more details, see section 9.4 below.

4.2.1 Spatial resolution and validity

The spatial resolution of WFD reference levels is the water body. Reference levels of chlorophyllÂ a differ between lake water body types. Depending on several typology factors (height above sea level, calcium concentration, humus concentration, and depth), lake water bodies are grouped in nine categories, each with their own set of reference levels (DGVF 2025, Tables 4.2â4.4).

5. Uncertainties

The main uncertainty for national and regional values of the indicator is sampling error. Measurements of variable values are only sampled in a small fraction of all relevant water bodies. The approach below extrapolates indicator values to water bodies that have not been sampled, but this extrapolation is necessarily uncertain. This uncertainty is quantified using prediction intervals.

The underlying problem of the mentioned uncertainty is that the representativeness of the sampled water bodies for the non-sampled water bodies is unknown. A specific issue regarding representativeness is that quite some WFD measurements are taken precisely because the sampled water body is known or assumed to be unrepresentative. The main reasons are the following:

  • Some water bodies are sampled because it is known or suspected that they do not fulfil the normative objective that X > X60 (in order to justify and design measures to improve ecological condition and, later, to evaluate the effect of the measures taken).
  • Some water bodies are sampled because they are regarded as reference water bodies, i.e.Â assumed to be in, or very close to, the reference condition.

The approach below attempts to correct for these biases by weighting measurements by the âsurveillance activityâ (overvÃ¥kingsaktivitet) during which they have been sampled. Scores between â3 and +3 have been assigned to each surveillance activity, where the sign indicates the direction of the deviation (poorer or better than a randomly chosen water body), and the absolute value is an estimate of the magnitude of the bias. The approach has been described (in Norwegian) by Sandvik (2019: pp.Â 17â19) and extended by Framstad et al.Â (2023: pp.Â 121â122).

7. Datasets

7.1 VannmiljÃ¸

VannmiljÃ¸ is a database maintained by the Norwegian Environment Agency that is used to collect registrations related to ecological condition of water according to the WFD. This database contains information on all measurements taken in connection with the WFD (âregistrationsâ) as well as all locations at which measurements are taken (âwater localitiesâ). Other information available from VannmiljÃ¸ includes lists of WFD variables and indicators (âparametersâ), of surveillance activities, of measurement units used, of species recorded etc.

The database has long been available for manual download via https://vannmiljo.miljodirektoratet.no. Recently, the data have also been made available via an API, which is utilised here.

7.2. Vannforekomster

In order to carry out the subsequent analyses, all WFD registrations need to be assigned to the correct water body (vannforekomst). Information on water bodies has currently to be downloaded from separate sources. A geospatial dataset of all water bodies is publicly available, but it needs to be downloaded manually:

  • Navigate to https://karteksport.miljodirektoratet.no.
  • In the menu to the left of the map, tick âVannforekomsterâ in the âProduktâ sectionâ¦
  • â¦and âNasjonaltâ in the âDefiner omrÃ¥deâ section.
  • Click âNesteâ.
  • Provide your e-mail in the âEpostâ box.
  • Choose âESRI Filgeodatabase (ESPG:4326)â in the âFormatâ box.
  • Upon pressing âSend bestillingâ, a compressed geodatabase (gdb) will be sent to your e-mail.

The uncompressed geodatabase is needed for the analyses. It has to have the name âVF.gdbâ and to be placed in the âdataâ folder in order to be recognised. (A cached version called âVF.RDataâ is used in the demo below.)

7.3. Vann-nett

In addition to the location of water bodies, the subsequent analyses need information on the water body typology. In WFD context, typology refers to a set of factors describing abiotic characteristics of the water bodies, such as altitude, size and alkalinity. This information is publicly available from a separate database called Vann-nett via the link https://vann-nett.no/waterbodies/report.

A spreadsheet workbook exported from Vann-nett is needed for the analyses. It has to have the name âV-L.csvâ (for lakes) or âV-R.csvâ (for rivers) in order to recognised.

(Note that Vann-nett has recently been upgraded. In the new version, typology factors are not included in the list of variables about water bodies that are available for export. For the time being, water body typology thus has to be based on an export from the previous version of Vann-nett, which is no longer online. It is to be hoped that the relevant information will be made available in the new version soon.)

7.4. InnsjÃ¸databasen

Detailed information on Norwegian lakes is available from the innsjÃ¸database (âlake databaseâ) maintained by the Norwegian Water Resources and Energy Directorate (NVE). This dataset is publicly available, but it needs to be downloaded manually:

  • Navigate to https://nedlasting.nve.no/gis/.
  • Choose (or retain) âVektordataâ in the âVelg datatypeâ dropdown menu.
  • Expand the âInnsjÃ¸â heading.
  • Tick the âInnsjÃ¸â box.
  • Click âNesteâ.
  • Choose âESRI shapefil (.shp)â in the âVelg kartformatâ dropdown menu.
  • Choose âGeografiske koordinater ETRS89â in the âVelg koordinatsystemâ dropdown menu.
  • Choose âOverlapperâ in the âVelg utvalgsmetodeâ dropdown menu.
  • Choose âLandsdekkendeâ in the âVelg dekningsomrÃ¥deâ dropdown menu.
  • Click âNesteâ.
  • Provide your e-mail address in the âE-postâ boxes.
  • Tick the âJeg har lest og forstÃ¥tt betingelserâ¦â box to accept the terms of use.
  • Upon pressing âSendâ, a link to a compressed archive (zip) will be sent to your e-mail.
  • Click that link to download the data.
  • Uncompress the zip archive. (Upon uncompression, the relevant files are located in the folder NVEKartdata\NVEData\Innsjo.)
  • Place the shapefiles (called Innsjo_Innsjo.*) in the âdataâ folder.

(A cached version called âNVE.RDataâ is used in the demo below.)

8. Spatial units

Data (measurements) are assumed to be representative for their respective water bodies, which correspond to the Ecosystem Assets of freshwater ecosystems. The Ecosystem Accounting Area covered by the data is mainland Norway.

We can show the raw (unfiltered and unscaled) measurements on a map.

Code 
{
  xaxis <- seq(0, 30, 5)
  dig <- 0
  snudd <- TRUE
  
  ml <- V[which(V$id %in% 
               VL$id[which(VL$lokid %in% 
                         DATA$lokid[which(DATA$verdi %mellom% range(xaxis))])]), ]
  ml$maaling <- NA
  for (i in 1:nrow(ml)) {
    ml$maaling[i] <- mean(DATA$verdi[which(DATA$lokid %in% 
                                             VL$lokid[which(VL$id == ml$id[i])])])
  }
  z <- 2
  fjern <- c()
  while (length(which(ml$maaling < xaxis[z])) == 0) {
    fjern <- c(fjern, z - 1)
    z <- z + 1
  }
  z <- length(xaxis) - 1
  while (length(which(ml$maaling > xaxis[z])) == 0) {
    fjern <- c(fjern, z + 1)
    z <- z - 1
  }
  if (length(fjern)) xaxis <- xaxis[-fjern]
  if (snudd) xaxis <- rev(xaxis)
  xlim <- range(xaxis)
  ml$maaling <- sapply(sapply(ml$maaling, max, xlim[1]), min, xlim[2])
  ml <- ml[order(ml$maaling, decreasing = !snudd), ]
  
  load("../data/Norge.map")
  par(mai = rep(0, 4))
  plot(Norge.kontur, xlim = c(3.5, 31.5), ylim = c(57.5, 71.5), 
       xaxs = "i", yaxs = "i", asp = 2, col = grey(0.84), border = NA)
  points(ml$long, ml$lat, pch = 20, cex = 0.6, col = if (snudd)
         farve(ml$maaling, xlim[2], xlim[1]) else 
         farve(ml$maaling, xlim[1], xlim[2]))
  text(6, 70, tittel, cex = 1.5, font = 2)
  for (i in seq(0, 0.999, 0.001)) {
    rect(24, 59+i*8, 26, 59+(i+0.001)*8, border = NA,
         col = if (snudd) farve(i, 1, 0) else farve(i, 0, 1))
  }
  rect(24, 59, 26, 67, lwd = 2)
  for (i in xaxis) {
    lines(c(24.0,23.6), rep(59 + 8 * (i-xlim[1]) / (xlim[2]-xlim[1]), 2), lwd=2)
  }
  text(23.6, 59 + 8 * (xaxis - xlim[1]) / (xlim[2] - xlim[1]), 
       erstatt(formatC((xaxis), dig, format = "f"), "-", "â"), pos = 2)
  if (length(unique(DATA$enhet)) %=% 1 & 
             unique(DATA$enhet) %!=% "3" & exists("Enheter")) {
    text(25, 58.5, Enheter[which(Enheter[, 1] == unique(DATA$enhet)), 2])
  }
}

9.4. Calculating mEQRs using reference levels

According to the WFD and DGVF (2025), measurements of WFD variables are transformed into so-called nEQR values (ânormalised Ecological Quality Ratiosâ) between 0 and 1, which correspond to indicator values sensu SEEA EA. This is normally done using the following steps:

  1. Truncation. Variable values are truncated, where measurements that are poorer than X0 are set to X0, and measurements that are better than X100 are set to X100.
  2. Scaling. The truncated variable values are linearly scaled so that X0 becomes 0 and X100 becomes 1. The resulting indicator values are referred to as EQRs (âEcological Quality Ratiosâ).
  3. Transformation. EQR values are transformed in a stepwise-linear manner, so that the indicator values 0.2, 0.4, 0.6 and 0.8 correspond to the thresholds between the normative definitions of âbadâ, âpoorâ, âmoderateâ, âgoodâ and âhighâ ecological status according to the WFD. The resulting indicator values are referred to as nEQRs (ânormalised EQRsâ).

Truncation, however, removes information about variation in ecological condition that is important for estimating (modelling and extrapolating) the indicator value and its uncertainty. Therefore, the dataflow from WFD to an Ecological Condition Account should be based on values that are scaled and transformed but not truncated. This is implemented in the current context by modifying the order of the steps from truncationâscalingâtransformation to scalingâtransformationâaggregationâtruncation (following Sandvik 2019: pp.Â 13â15, Sandvik 2025):

  1. Scaling. The untruncated variable values are linearly scaled so that X0 becomes 0 and X100 becomes 1. Note that the resulting values may be negative (if X is poorer than X0) or larger than 1 (if X is better than X100).
  2. Transformation. The scaled values are transformed in a stepwise-linear manner in accordance with the threshold values defined by the WFD. The resulting indicator values are here referred to as mEQRs (âmodified EQRsâ). This step requires an adjustment in cases were the minimum and/or maximum values of X can be much lower or higher than X0 or X100. The approach chosen here ensures that no indicator value can be below â0.2 or above 1.2.
  3. Aggregration. Indicator values for the specific water bodies need to be spatially aggregated (see below).
  4. Truncation. When mEQR values are truncated, they become identical to nEQR values. However, truncation is here done only after the spatial aggregation of the modelled and simulated values.

Let us have closer look at the reference levels of the indicator (which are given in DGVF 2025).

9.5. Estimating the indicator values and their uncertainty

With the necessary files in place, the calculations can start. This is done using the function WFD2ECA (âWater Framework Directive to Ecological Condition Accountâ), which is documented in the WFD2ECA repository (Sandvik 2025). The function produces summaries of the steps performed (for the time being, the information is provided in Norwegian only).

  iterasjoner = 1000,
  SEED = 479001600,
  vis = FALSE
)

10. Results

As reference values of chlorophyllÂ a differ between water body types and the scaling function used is non-linear, aggregated averages of unscaled values (variable values sensu SEEA EA) are not informative. Therefore, this indicator is reported in terms of scaled values only (nEQR sensu WFD; indicator values sensu SEEA EA).

The results are here tabulated (a) for the whole country and different years, and (b) for regions in 2024. These estimates are based on 10,000 iterations and therefore differ from the ones above.

NB: Please note that these results are not the final ones for 2024. The deadline for reporting WFD measurements taken in 2024 is September 2025, meaning that the values for 2024 are so far based mainly on measurements taken in 2022 and 2023.
